# We test everything on ourselves first

One more rule I want to write about. I already wrote that when we onboard a new person, we build them a second brain. And when it comes to building any new feature, we have a rule: test everything on ourselves first.

We do not release a product, a tool, or a routine until it has made our own life easier first. Our own team is our first market and our first honest test.

Here is the point. If a thing is good only on paper, and in real life none of us uses it, then it is either not needed by anyone or simply badly made. You see it right away, on your own people, before a single client ever lays eyes on it.

It looks like this. Any new thing, be it a second brain, a skill, or an automation, I break in first. Then Natasha and Ruslana. And a few days later we look: are we actually using it, or did it turn out that nobody needs it.

And this way the excess falls off by itself. When you live with the thing yourself, you stop wasting time on what looks pretty but does not help in the work. You build exactly what you yourself are missing every single day.

There are downsides too, if only because it comes out slower. But it is all so that only what we use ourselves ever goes outside.

Probably that is how it should be. I do not recommend to others what I do not use myself and do not know inside out.

What about you? Do you build only for others? Or do you actually use what you make yourself?

